history.content:
It's as much as you need to until you feel most comfortable with the material.

It is a myth that top students only do a couple of practice exams. This may be true for some people, but not everyone. It's a personal thing.

children.subject:
I agree with the student answer. I found 61C and similar classes (i.e 162) to be more intuitive than classes like 70/170. I pulled an A in 61C and 162 doing just 3 - 4 past exams for each exam. However, for 70/170 I would still manage to mess up on exams even if I went over 6+ older exams in depth.

On the contrary, one of my friends can think about 70/170 problems really well. He could ace those tests doing almost no practice at all, but he has a harder time in classes like 61C and 162.

A more relevant question to ask yourself is how do you feel about the material and you should do that much past exams accordingly. I find that doing 3-4 past exams in more intuitive subjects is enough for me, whereas I might need to do 6+ on harder subjects, but that's just me.

Wow you peeps go hard. The only classes I've ever done multiple actual practice tests is 61A, my first time programming. Everything else was a practice test and hella practice problems on the parts I needed to focus on learning.

history.content: How many past exams should an average student do to prepare well for tests in classes like 61C  CS 170 CS172? Is doing 8 practice exams too much? Is it a myth that top students only do a couple of practice tests?
